    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        populus iterum magnus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The people powerful again.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Nisi in uarias Romanoru[m] Leges, et sa[e]p&egrave; dissimillimas diligenter, intimeq[ue] penetrassem; qua[e] pla[e]runq[ue] non tam rerum ratione, qu&agrave;m 
                        personarum respectu sunt lata[e]: nunq[uam] de istius status politico, pathetic&oacute;ue progressu, aliquid potuissem solidi, aut certi statuere. 
                        Nunc video rationem aliquando; respectum sa[e]p&egrave;; affectum sa[e]pi&ugrave;s, invalescere. In turbine Quid non?
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>If I had not carefully and profoundly scrutinized the various and often highly different laws of the Romans, proposed mostly not so much for 
                practical reasons, as out of regard for persons, I could never have established anything sound or certain about the political or affective progress of this 
                constitutional form. Now I occasionally see that reason, often regard, very often emotion predominates. What does not happen in a turbulent time?
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Appiu[m] reum">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Appius reus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Appius Claudius Crassus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Appius defendant. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Iteru[m] ad populum prouocatio: vel ab ipso Appio. Nimis, vt fit, in prosperis inflato; in aduersis abiecto.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Appius Claudius Crassus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Again an appeal to the people: indeed by Appius himself, who was, as so happens, puffed up too much in favourable, 
                and thrown out in bad times.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Potestas tribunitia, et libertas plebis: qu&ograve; gravior, e&ograve; leuior. Nihil in populo fundatum, vbi senatus tant&ograve; profundior: patritij opibus, artibus, 
                        auctoritate, meritis, omni deniq[ue] magnificentia tant&ograve; instructiores. In populo plus potestatis: in Senatu plus dignitatis. Illi valent omnes: 
                        hi florent singuli; et citi&ugrave;s, seriusve rerum potiuntur.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The power of the tribunes and plebeian liberty: the greater it is, the slighter. It is so much weightier, when there is a senate, and 
                nothing is based on the people. The patricians are so much more prepared, with their means, skills, authority, rights and finally, with their grandeur. 
                There is more power in the people, and more dignity in the senate. The former are powerful collectively, the latter shine individually, 
                and they seize control over affairs more quickly or more slowly.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
